Introduction

 

 

Welcome to the powerful Fornux® PowerCalc!

 

Render beautiful 2D/3D graphics and histogram/scatter plot quickly with smart formatting, trace your graphic coordinates, zoom/translate and send professional reports in seconds. Enter your data as a vector, matrix, fraction, angle, sexagesimal or base-n number to compute any scientific, logical, vectorial, linear and statistical operations including standard deviations and nonlinear regressions. Fornux® PowerCalc comes with a complete documentation, recognizes expressions having polynomials with implicit multiplications, affects entire expression to any variable upon request (thus programmable), spaces your operators intelligently and much more!

Binary, octal, decimal and hexadecimal calculations

Binary, octal, decimal and hexadecimal conversions

 

  • .The 16, 10, 8, 2 numeric base is set by respectively selecting the appropriate  radio button. 

  • .Fractional part of floating point numbers is implicitly truncated when converted to hexadecimal, octal and binary numeric base. 

  • .Hexadecimal, octal and binary integers are 64 bits long, so it is possible to cast the integer part of a decimal value to and from its original value. 

  • .Negative numbers in hexadecimal, octal and binary number base are expressed as two’s complement. 

  • .Calculation range for each hexadecimal, octal and binary number base does not exceed [-9,223,372,036,854,775,808.; 9,223,372,036,854,775,807.]. 

  • .You can use neither scientific function nor special trigonometric and statistical calculations using a hexadecimal, octal or binary number base.

Basic matrix operations

 

  • .A matrix is enclosed with nested brackets [[], [], …] and can contain any type of element (any form of number or fractions). 

  • .To find the determinant of a matrix, use the vertical bars by pressing the  button.

  • .Matrices can be added, subtracted, multiplied and divided by a scalar variable.

Statistical calculations

Standard deviation

 

  • .Data is represented as a simple vector. 

  • .Either multiple data of the same value can be input after the data itself by repeatedly pressing  or by typing the number of times the data is repeated in braces. 

 

Unbiased estimate of standard deviation [√variance(v)]

σ n − 1 = 1 n − 1 ∑ i= 1 n ( v i − v ¯ ) 2
 

Maximum likelihood of standard deviation [√variancemle(v)]

σ n = 1 n ∑ i= 1 n ( v i − v ¯ ) 2
 

Mean [mean(v)]

v ¯ = 1 n ∑ i= 1 n v i
 

Median [median(v)]

If n is odd

v ~ =v n / 2
 

If n is even

v ~ = v n / 2 +v n / 2 + 1 2

Regression

 

 

  • .The data is represented as a vector having vectors of 2 elements representing [x, y]. 

  • .Multiple data of the same value can be input after the data itself by repeatedly pressing
    .
    . 

 

Constant term [α(w)]

α= ∑ i= 1 n w yi − β ∑ i= 1 n w xi n
 

Regression coefficient [β(w)]

β= ∑ i= 1 n w xi w yi − n w ¯ x w ¯ y ∑ i= 1 n w xi 2 − n w ¯ x 2
 

Correlation coefficient [γ(w)]

γ= n ∑ i= 1 n w xi w yi − ∑ i= 1 n w xi ∑ i= 1 n w yi [ n ∑ i= 1 n w xi 2 − ( ∑ i= 1 n w xi ) 2 ] [ n ∑ i= 1 n w yi 2 − ( ∑ i= 1 n w yi ) 2 ]

Logarithmic regression

 

  • .Enter the x data as the logarithm ln(x) and the y data inputs the same as that for linear regression. 

  • .Example: In “Example\statistics.fcv”, see variable L (CTRL + E, L) for a graphical example (remark: you need to affect the variable K with its previous expression if you modify the contents of J). 

 

Formula

y=α+β ⋅ ln x
 

Estimated values

y ^ =α+β ⋅ ln x
 
x ^ =e y − α β
 

 

Exponential regression

 

  • .Enter the y data as the logarithm ln(y) and the x data inputs the same as that for linear regression. 

  • .The constant term α is obtained with: е^α(w), where w is a vector of paired variables. 

  • .Example: In “Example\statistics.fcv”, see variable P (CTRL + E, P) for a graphical example (remark: you need to affect the variable O with its previous expression if you modify the contents of N). 

 

Formula

y=α ⋅ e βx
 

Estimated values

y=α ⋅ e βx
 
x ^ = ln y − ln α β
 

 

Power regression

 

  • .Enter the both x and y data as the logarithm ln(x) and ln(y). 

  • .The constant term α is obtained with: е^α(w), where w is a vector of paired variables. 

  • .Example: In “Example\statistics.fcv”, see variable T (CTRL + E, T) for a graphical example (remark: you need to affect the variable S with its previous expression if you modify the contents of R). 

 

Formula

y=α ⋅ x β
 

Estimated values

y=α ⋅ x β
 
x ^ =e ln y − ln α β
 

 

Graphics

Range parameters

 

  • .You can lookup and specify new range parameters for the x, y and z coordinates by selecting Settings → Range. 

  • .Each range parameter consist of a minimum, maximum and a scale factor (distance between hash marks). 

  • .The range settings are automatically adjusted before displaying histograms and scatter plots when Settings → Graphic → Adjust range settings when displaying histograms and scatter plots is checked. 

  • .You can reset the range settings by pressing Settings → Range → Defaults button and then Ok. 

 

2D function graphs

The product of all the integers up to and including the given integer x.

 

 

 

| x |

Absolute Value

 

The numerical value x regardless of its sign.

 

 

 

 

Basic functions

 

ln(x)

Natural Logarithm

 

The logarithm of x having base е.

 

 

 

log(x)

Logarithm

 

The exponent required to produce x in base 10.

 

 

 

еxp(x)

Exponential

 

Base of the natural logarithm.  

 

 

 

floor(x)

Integer part

 

Gives the largest integer less than or equal to x.

 

 

 

ran()

Random number

 

Returns a random number between [0.001, 0.999].  Repeated calls to ran() generate random numbers with a uniform distribution.

 

 

 

 

Combinatorics

 

 

permutation(x, y)

Permutation

 

Returns the arrangement of any determinate number of things in all possible orders, one after the other.

 

 

combination(x, y)

Combination

 

Returns the different arrangements of a number of objects into groups.

 

 

 

 

Geometry

 

 

polar(v)

Polar conversion of rectangular coordinates

 

Converts rectangular coordinates into polar coordinates (distance from a fixed pole and angle from a fixed line passing through the pole).  

 

 

 

 

rectangular(v)

Rectangular conversion of polar coordinates

 

Converts polar coordinates into rectangular coordinates (rectilinear two-dimensional x, y coordinates).

Vector functions

sort(u)

Sort

 

Sorts a vector in ascending order.

 

 

Tools → Insert → sort(u)

part(i, u)

i’th member

 

Returns the i’th element of a vector.

 

 

Tools → Insert → part(i, u)

merge(u, v)

Merge

 

Creates a vector having elements in both u and v.

 

 

Tools → Insert → merge(u, v)

length(v)

Number of element

 

Gives the number of elements in v.

 

 

 

sum(v)

Sum

 

Gives the total of the elements in v:

∑ i= 1 n v i
 

 

 

product(v)

Product

 

Gives the product of the elements in v:

∏ i= 1 n v i
 

 

 

mean(v)

Mean

 

Unweighted average of the elements in v:

v ¯ = 1 n ∑ i= 1 n v i
 

 

 

median(v)

Median

 

Middle value of the elements in v:

If n is odd

v ~ =v n / 2
 

If n is even

v ~ = v n / 2 +v n / 2 + 1 2
 

 

 

√variance(v)

Unbiased estimate of standard deviation

 

Standard deviation using sample data of population v:

σ n − 1 = 1 n − 1 ∑ i= 1 n ( v i − v ¯ ) 2
 

 

 

√variancemle(v)

Maximum likelihood of standard deviation

 

Standard deviation using all data of finite population v:

σ n = 1 n ∑ i= 1 n ( v i − v ¯ ) 2

Matrix functions

 

sumxy(w)

Sum of individual products

X column

 

Transposes a vector of paired variables and returns its first vector representing x values of w.

 

 

 

coly(w)

Y column

 

Transposes a vector of paired variables and returns its second vector representing y values of w.

Transposition

 

Transposes a rectangular matrix.

 

 

Tools → Insert → transpose(w)

α(w)

Constant term of regression

 

Constant term of regression given by:

α= ∑ i= 1 n w yi − β ∑ i= 1 n w xi n
 

ALT + Z, ALT + L, ALT + A

 

β(w)

Regression coefficient of regression

 

Regression coefficient given by:

β= ∑ i= 1 n w xi w yi − n w ¯ x w ¯ y ∑ i= 1 n w xi 2 − n w ¯ x 2
 

ALT + Z, ALT + L, ALT + B

 

γ(w)

Correlation coefficient of regression

 

Quantity which gives the quality of a least squares fitting to the original data:

γ= n ∑ i= 1 n w xi w yi − ∑ i= 1 n w xi ∑ i= 1 n w yi [ n ∑ i= 1 n w xi 2 − ( ∑ i= 1 n w xi ) 2 ] [ n ∑ i= 1 n w yi 2 − ( ∑ i= 1 n w yi ) 2 ]
 

ALT + Z, ALT + L, ALT + G

Other

 

result(x)

Copy of the result of an expression

 

Evaluates the expression in x and returns a copy of the result.  This is useful to increment a value relative to its old value while avoiding recursivity.

 

 

Tools → Insert → result(x)

Technical Specs

Calculation range

[-1e4923; 1e4923]

Infinity representation

NAN

Not-A-Number representation

NAN

Base-N range

[-9,223,372,036,854,775,80810; 9,223,372,036,854,775,80710]

Base-N integer size

64 bits

Rounding

Internal calculations use up to 64 decimal places of precision.  The displayed value is rounded according to the specified number of decimal places (maximum of 60).

Number of steps

Expressions having more than 1000 depth levels of variable lookups will be considered infinitely recursive.

Number of variables

26 variables.

Number of functions

36 functions, 10 operators and 8 binary operators.

 

Bugs and limitations

 

  • .Infinite numbers are regarded as being unreal numbers (NAN). 

  • .Results higher than [-1e4923; 1e4923] is undefined (may be represented as NAN). 

  • .Graphical range limits cannot be lower or higher than [-1e308; 1e308].
